Three agents — a telemetry operator at the ground station, a subsystem engineer at the operations desk, and a flight director at the operations console — coordinate over a single comm link to recover a satellite during each contact window across {{ round_count }} rounds. Every character sent on the link costs one simulated second (fixed per-round contact window: {{ contact_window_seconds }}s). If total communication time exceeds the window, the satellite passes out of view and the round fails.

The same telemetry readings can require different command sequences depending on the satellite's current mode, power state, thermal state, and what flight is authorizing this pass, so the telemetry operator cannot solve a round alone. The subsystem engineer holds a live command resolver that rotates wait times every round — they cannot solve alone either, because they cannot see live authorization rules. The flight director sees the live authorization envelope — which commands are allowed, which are forbidden, and any ordering dependencies — but cannot diagnose the telemetry pattern. Every round, all three perspectives must combine before the operator calls send_command_sequence.

Fourteen named telemetry patterns are combined into per-round cases ({{ pattern_count_min }}–{{ pattern_count_max }} patterns per pass, drawn from the catalog by a deterministic seed). Command sequences are rendered each round with a rotating wait-time offset so even agents that memorize the pattern names cannot bypass asking the engineer for the current procedure.

Round success requires all of: the submitted sequence matches the engineer's command resolver, follows the required order, includes the correct wait times for every step, contains no action forbidden by flight, satisfies every authorization dependency, omits no required step, and stays within the contact window. The LLM judge scores the criteria per round; the contact window is checked deterministically.
